  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most countries and is typically addressed under criminal legislation. It is considered a serious financial crime that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, making it appear as if it comes from a legitimate source. \n\nKey points about money laundering in criminal law include:\n\n1. It is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions worldwide\n\n2. Penalties can include:\n- Significant fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n\n3. Covered under various legal frameworks such as:\n- Criminal codes\n- Anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Financial crime statutes\n\n4. Often involves multiple stages:\n- Placement\n- Layering\n- Integration\n\n5. Typically prosecuted by specialized financial crime units or prosecutors\n\nThe specific legal details and penalties vary between countries, but money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity designed to legitimize proceeds from illegal activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption.",
